Tutorial: Analysis of Top Streamers on Twitch¶

Introduction¶

In the past few years, people have reduced the frequency of outdoor activities due to the spread of the epidemic. This phenomenon has given rise to the rapid growth of the live-streaming industry, with many people choosing to spend time watching live streams at home during the epidemic.

In this tutorial, we'll analyze the top 1000 Twitch streamer in 2021. This data is available on kaggle. According to the instructions, the data will be updated once a year, but the 2022 version has not been updated yet, so we will start with the 2021 data.

We will go over loading data, organizing data, analyzing data. We can also formulate some hypotheses from the data and prove them by statistical methods. We hope our analysis can provide some insights for other people who want to become Streamers.

Data¶

Explanation of this dataset:

  • Channel: The name of this streamer
  • Watch time: Total time this streamer was watched
  • Stream time: Total time this streamer streaming
  • Peak viewers: The highest viewer at the same time this year
  • Average viewers: The average time this streamer was watched
  • Followers: number of followers
  • Followers gained: number of followers gained this year
  • Views gained: number of views gained this year
  • Partnered: is this streamer works for Twitch.tv
  • Mature: is this streamer age > 18
  • Language: what language does this streamer speak

At this stage, we want to add some new columns, that would benefit our following analysis. Pinpointing to the fact that The earlier Streamer starts live-streaming, the more likely it is to accumulate more followers.

It is not fair to compare the number of followers across streamer, we should rather compare the percentage of growth in followers. We can use the following formula to do this

Growth = Followers Gained / ( Followers - Followers Gained )

Growth would be a float number, indicate the growth of followers for each streamer in terms of rate.

In [58]:
data['Growth'] = data['Followers gained'] / (data['Followers'] - data['Followers gained'])
data['Growth'].describe()

Data Exploration and Analysis¶

We already have a general understanding of this data, next we need to explore the value of the data to obtain more useful information.

Data exploration and analysis is defined as the process of examining a dataset in order to gain insights and better understand its characteristics. This typically involves using various techniques and tools to explore the data, such as visualizing the data using graphs and charts, summarizing the data using descriptive statistics, and looking for patterns and trends in the data. The goal of data exploration and analysis is to discover useful information that can help inform decision-making and guide further research or investigation.

Heat Map¶

Heatmap can be used to visualize the correlation between different variables in a dataset, or to identify areas where certain events or activities are concentrated.

  sns.heatmap(data.corr());

The closer the color is to white, the stronger the correlation between the two variables. Following variables seems to have closer relationship:

  • Watch time and Views gained
  • Followers and Followers Gained
  • Peak viewers and Followers

Let's investigate further first on Watch time and Views gained. We plot watch time vs views gained

Quite obvious that the two variables are linearly related. In statistics, a linear relationship is a relationship between two variables that can be represented by a straight line. This means that if one variable increases or decreases, the other variable also increases or decreases at a constant rate.

However, that's not enough, let's see if other factor plays a role in this relation. For example, look into language. Since English is taking the majority. We can consider all other languages as Non-English.

In [127]:
def language_to_color(l):
    if l == 'English':
        return "orangered"
    return "skyblue"


fig4, ax = plt.subplots(1 ,1, figsize=(12, 8))
ax.scatter(x=data['Watch time(Minutes)'], y=data['Views gained'], c=data['Language'].apply(language_to_color))

This isn't clear enough, we can add a line of best fit, to see if there's a difference.

We use sklearn to do this. Sklearn is a machine learning library for the Python programming language. It is designed to provide a simple and efficient way to integrate machine learning into applications, and contains a wide range of algorithms for classification, regression, clustering, and other common tasks in machine learning. Linear Regression is one of the most basic.

In [139]:
def language_to_color(l):
    if l == 'English':
        return "orangered"
    return "skyblue"

data_copied_0 = data.copy()
data_copied_0['isEnglish'] = data_copied_0['Language'] == 'English'
x_max = max(data['Watch time(Minutes)'])

fig5, ax = plt.subplots(1 ,1, figsize=(12, 8))
ax.scatter(x=data_copied_0['Watch time(Minutes)'], y=data_copied_0['Views gained'], c=data_copied_0['Language'].apply(language_to_color))
ax.set_xlabel('Watch time (Minutes)')
ax.set_ylabel('Views gained')
ax.set_title('Views gained V.S Watch time', loc='center')

import matplotlib.lines as mlines
english_mark = mlines.Line2D([], [], color='orangered', marker='o', linestyle='None',
                          markersize=7, label='English')
non_english_mark  = mlines.Line2D([], [], color='skyblue', marker='o', linestyle='None',
                          markersize=7, label='Non-English')
ax.legend(handles=[english_mark, non_english_mark])


from sklearn.linear_model import LinearRegression
for c,dl in data_copied_0.groupby(['isEnglish']):
    import numpy as np
    X = np.array(dl['Watch time(Minutes)']).reshape(-1, 1)
    Y = dl['Views gained']
    # create regression line
    reg = LinearRegression().fit(X, Y)
    # pretty print the model
    sign = "+" if reg.intercept_ > 0 else "-"
    ax.add_line(mlines.Line2D(alpha=0.5, ls='--', xdata=[0, x_max], ydata=[reg.predict([[0]]), reg.predict([[x_max]])], c="orangered" if c else "skyblue"))

In a linear regression model, the dependent variable is predicted from the independent variable using a linear equation. This equation takes the form Y = a + bX, where X is the independent variable, Y is the dependent variable, 'a' is the intercept, and 'b' is the slope of the line. Linear regression is used to analyze the relationship between two variables and to make predictions about the dependent variable based on the value of the independent variable.

As can be seen from the figure, the slopes of the two regression lines are not the same. Means they have different 'b'. This suggests that language speaking plays a role in affecting views gained. For the same amount of watch time, streamer who speak non-english get a higher views than those speak english. Frankly speaking, this is counter-intuitive, because people who watch Twitter mainly speaks English.

Next, we use similar approach to check if Mature and Partner plays a role in this relationship.

The first graph indicates that being an adult is also one of the factors that affects View Gained. For two Streamers with the same Watch time, the minor one may have more Views.

The second graph wasn't so meaningful because the input is highly unbalanced. By this, it means that there are too many samples being partnered, but too less for non-partnered, the regression line for non-partnered is not that reliable.

For other co-relations, we can explore the relationships present in the data in the same way. Due to space issues, we are not showing other similar explorations

We next prove in a more mathematical way that these relations hold.

Hypothesis testing¶
